Macquarie Capital enhances aerospace, defense and government services coverage with appointment of David Farkas to Managing Director Business Wire Mon, Jan 27, 2025, 4:30 PM 3 min read NEW YORK, January 27, 2025 --( BUSINESS WIRE )-- Macquarie Capital , the corporate advisory, capital markets and principal investing arm of Macquarie Group, today announced the appointment of David Farkas as Managing Director, enhancing its aerospace, defense and government services (ADG) advisory practice. Mr. Farkas has nearly 20 years of experience across the aerospace and defense industry, both in mergers and acquisitions and as a corporate executive. He has led complex M&A transactions and portfolio transformations in verticals such as engines and mechanical systems, aftermarket repairs and overhauls, space and satellite systems, avionics, communications and connectivity technologies, hypersonic technologies and aerospace decarbonization technologies. Mr. Farkas previously held senior leadership positions at Honeywell International, including leading corporate development and M&A for Honeywell’s Aerospace business, and he served as the Senior Executive for M&A and business development at GE Aerospace. Most recently, he was a senior advisor at AlixPartners and Renaissance Strategic Partners, where he advised clients across aerospace and defense on M&A and industry trends. Mr. Farkas received his bachelor’s degree from Michigan State University and his MBA from the University of Queensland. "David’s knowledge, depth of experience and reputation in the aerospace and defense industry will be immensely valuable as we support our corporate and financial sponsor clients in identifying and executing on growth opportunities," said Tim Alden, Co-head of Aerospace, Defense and Government Services coverage at Macquarie Capital. Macquarie Capital’s ADG advisory team expects the sector to see strong M&A interest in 2025 as corporates continue to evaluate their portfolios and financial sponsors seek opportunities to create value. "The aerospace and defense sector continues to experience strong demand for commercial air travel, transformation from technological advances and growth amid the heightened global security environment," said Mr. Farkas. "As corporates evaluate and potentially reshape their portfolios and sponsors seek entry points into the industry, the Macquarie Capital platform is well-positioned to support clients with unique solutions for this critical sector." Jeremy Parker, Co-head of Aerospace, Defense and Government Services coverage at Macquarie Capital added, "David brings extensive commercial and strategic experience in the sector, which complements the team’s existing background across aerospace, defense and government services. We are delighted to welcome him to our team." Story Continues In addition to M&A advisory services, Macquarie Capital also provides debt and equity solutions, including principal investments from its balance sheet. Previous M&A transactions in the ADG sector include advising on the sale of Azure Summit Technology to CACI International Inc., advising Alion Science and Technology Corp. on its sale to Huntington Ingalls Industries, and advising Abaco Systems on its sale to AMETEK. About Macquarie Capital Macquarie Capital is the advisory, capital markets and principal investment arm of Macquarie Group. It encompasses corporate advisory, a full spectrum of capital solutions, including capital raising services from equity, debt and private capital markets and principal investments from Macquarie’s balance sheet. Macquarie Capital has deep sector expertise in the aerospace, defense and government services, consumer, gaming and leisure, critical minerals, energy, financial institutions, healthcare, industrials, infrastructure, real estate, services, software, technology, telecommunications and media sectors. Lockheed Martin Earnings: What To Look For From LMT Anthony Lee Mon, Jan 27, 2025, 4:02 PM 2 min read In This Article: LMT -1.63% Lockheed Martin Earnings: What To Look For From LMT Security and Aerospace company Lockheed Martin (NYSE:LMT) will be announcing earnings results tomorrow before market hours. Here’s what to look for. Lockheed Martin missed analysts’ revenue expectations by 1.5% last quarter, reporting revenues of $17.1 billion, up 1.3% year on year. It was a slower quarter for the company, with a significant miss of analysts’ EBITDA estimates and a slight miss of analysts’ organic revenue estimates. Is Lockheed Martin a buy or sell going into earnings? Read our full analysis here, it’s free . This quarter, analysts are expecting Lockheed Martin’s revenue to be flat year on year at $18.79 billion, in line with its flat revenue from the same quarter last year. Adjusted earnings are expected to come in at $6.61 per share. Lockheed Martin Total Revenue Analysts covering the company have generally reconfirmed their estimates over the last 30 days, suggesting they anticipate the business to stay the course heading into earnings. Lockheed Martin has only missed Wall Street’s revenue estimates once over the last two years, exceeding top-line expectations by 3.6% on average. Looking at Lockheed Martin’s peers in the aerospace and defense segment, some have already reported their Q4 results, giving us a hint as to what we can expect. CACI delivered year-on-year revenue growth of 14.5%, beating analysts’ expectations by 2.9%, and AAR reported revenues up 25.8%, topping estimates by 4.9%. CACI traded down 9.3% following the results while AAR was up 8.6%. Read our full analysis of CACI’s results here and AAR’s results here . There has been positive sentiment among investors in the aerospace and defense segment, with share prices up 4.9% on average over the last month. Lockheed Martin is up 3.4% during the same time and is heading into earnings with an average analyst price target of $559.61 (compared to the current share price of $496.96).
